WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.960
CHRIS: Good afternoon, everyone.

00:00:01.960 --> 00:00:04.740
Just a quick introduction
to our veteran guru

00:00:04.740 --> 00:00:06.940
overall finance guy, Wes Gray.

00:00:10.915 --> 00:00:12.290
WESLEY GRAY:
Thanks, Chris, and I

00:00:12.290 --> 00:00:14.120
appreciate you inviting
me here to Google.

00:00:14.120 --> 00:00:16.620
I actually have a huge
respect for the firm,

00:00:16.620 --> 00:00:19.500
we use it both personally
and for business.

00:00:19.500 --> 00:00:21.920
And I'm the founder
of Alpha Architect,

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:25.690
and our business is focused
on empowering investors

00:00:25.690 --> 00:00:26.980
through education.

00:00:26.980 --> 00:00:30.680
And part of our effort is
we do a ton of research,

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:32.350
including writing books.

00:00:32.350 --> 00:00:35.370
And one book we've written
with a couple my colleagues,

00:00:35.370 --> 00:00:39.870
Jack Bogle and David Folk, is
"The Do-It-Yourself Financial

00:00:39.870 --> 00:00:41.280
Advisor."

00:00:41.280 --> 00:00:45.870
And the thesis of this book is
that financial advice, as it

00:00:45.870 --> 00:00:50.450
currently stands, is too
complex and too opaque,

00:00:50.450 --> 00:00:54.520
but you can make it
simple and transparent.

00:00:54.520 --> 00:00:58.240
And a potential thing
we should consider

00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:02.640
is if financial advice can
be simple and transparent

00:01:02.640 --> 00:01:04.450
and still be effective.

00:01:04.450 --> 00:01:07.580
Maybe we don't need
intermediaries and all

00:01:07.580 --> 00:01:09.520
these expensive advisors.

00:01:09.520 --> 00:01:11.920
And so that's the
argument here, is

00:01:11.920 --> 00:01:14.466
that do-it-yourself
is not for everyone,

00:01:14.466 --> 00:01:15.465
but it's not impossible.

00:01:18.210 --> 00:01:20.790
So what is the problem
with advice that's

00:01:20.790 --> 00:01:23.740
too complex and too opaque?

00:01:23.740 --> 00:01:28.080
Well, you make the wolf of
Wall Street really rich.

00:01:28.080 --> 00:01:30.190
Why is advice complex?

00:01:30.190 --> 00:01:32.600
Because complexity sells.

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:37.190
If I'm a broker or an advisor
and I say, go buy and hold

00:01:37.190 --> 00:01:39.130
Vanguard funds
forever, you're going

00:01:39.130 --> 00:01:41.760
to say well, why the heck do
I need you to be my advisor?

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:43.840
Why am I paying
you all this money?

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:49.490
So advice has to be complex,
even though it may not work,

00:01:49.490 --> 00:01:51.250
because it sells.

00:01:51.250 --> 00:01:54.720
So this is what
we face out there.

00:01:54.720 --> 00:01:56.550
What is the problem with that?

00:01:56.550 --> 00:01:58.780
Let me orient it to this slide.

00:01:58.780 --> 00:02:03.190
So on the x-axis you
have Goldman Sachs,

00:02:03.190 --> 00:02:06.310
which epitomizes the
smartest people in the room.

00:02:06.310 --> 00:02:08.850
If anyone can beat the
market, Goldman Sachs

00:02:08.850 --> 00:02:10.570
should be able to beat
the market, right?

00:02:10.570 --> 00:02:12.300
And over here on
the right you have

00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:15.800
Vanguard, which is the exact
opposite of Goldman Sachs.

00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:17.710
They don't even try
to beat the market,

00:02:17.710 --> 00:02:21.160
they say we're going to
deliver you the market exposure

00:02:21.160 --> 00:02:24.280
at the lowest cost possible.

00:02:24.280 --> 00:02:29.750
On the y-axis right here, we
have the percentage of funds

00:02:29.750 --> 00:02:32.870
by these respective
entities-- the smartest people

00:02:32.870 --> 00:02:35.210
in the room and Vanguard.

00:02:35.210 --> 00:02:38.020
And these are the percentage
of funds that over the last 10

00:02:38.020 --> 00:02:43.340
years-- from '04 to 2014-- that
beat their respective benchmark

00:02:43.340 --> 00:02:44.440
indices.

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:48.440
Goldman sits
unfortunately around 10%.

00:02:48.440 --> 00:02:54.470
So 1 out of 10 funds provided
by Goldman Sachs-- which is just

00:02:54.470 --> 00:02:57.040
an example of the smartest
people in the room--

00:02:57.040 --> 00:02:59.730
doesn't beat the
passive benchmark.

00:02:59.730 --> 00:03:04.880
Whereas Vanguard over here has
a hit rate of around 45% to 50%,

00:03:04.880 --> 00:03:05.780
which makes sense.

00:03:05.780 --> 00:03:08.080
If I'm not trying to
beat the benchmark,

00:03:08.080 --> 00:03:10.080
I'm going to have some
that wins some that lose,

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:11.950
but on average I'm
going to be average.

00:03:11.950 --> 00:03:13.200
Great.

00:03:13.200 --> 00:03:17.864
What do you notice
between these two folks?

00:03:17.864 --> 00:03:22.840
The key difference is the
average fee charge-- 120 basis

00:03:22.840 --> 00:03:27.950
points or 1.2% for the
average Goldman fund,

00:03:27.950 --> 00:03:32.150
17 basis points for the
average Vanguard fund.

00:03:32.150 --> 00:03:37.040
So 1/6 the cost with
way better performance.

00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:40.860
And as Jack Bogle says here,
who's the smart money now?

00:03:40.860 --> 00:03:44.660
So just because you are really
smart and you're an expert

00:03:44.660 --> 00:03:46.220
and you have all
the expertise, that

00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:49.110
doesn't mean that your
clients end up winning.

00:03:49.110 --> 00:03:51.860
You may win, but the
clients may not win.

00:03:51.860 --> 00:03:53.390
So we need to consider this.

00:03:53.390 --> 00:03:56.410
And this is the problem
with too much complexity

00:03:56.410 --> 00:04:02.050
and not enough transparency,
is the wolf gets rich.

00:04:02.050 --> 00:04:05.310
We don't, as the clients.

00:04:05.310 --> 00:04:06.720
So what is the solution?

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:10.030
Well, the reality-- just from
an evidence-based perspective--

00:04:10.030 --> 00:04:12.940
is that financial
advice can be incredibly

00:04:12.940 --> 00:04:15.480
simple and transparent.

00:04:15.480 --> 00:04:18.260
And the simplest
thing that we could do

00:04:18.260 --> 00:04:21.420
is what we call the
60/40 portfolio.

00:04:21.420 --> 00:04:27.730
60% in a global stock index,
40% in a global bond Index.

00:04:27.730 --> 00:04:30.610
You could probably manage
this in your underwear

00:04:30.610 --> 00:04:34.190
from your dorm room for 15
to 20 basis points, right?

00:04:34.190 --> 00:04:37.510
Totally easy and actually
really effective.

00:04:37.510 --> 00:04:41.130
If you look historically,
this portfolio works.

00:04:41.130 --> 00:04:44.140
So if anyone's going to
add layers of complexity,

00:04:44.140 --> 00:04:47.680
they need to be benchmarked
against the cheapest,

00:04:47.680 --> 00:04:51.150
most liquid, and simple
porfolio that one can imagine.

00:04:51.150 --> 00:04:54.080
And I'm only going to
believe your extra complexity

00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:57.920
if you can show me via evidence
that it actually is superior.

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:06.610
One of the biggest
challenges to DIY the expert.

00:05:06.610 --> 00:05:08.870
Don't listen to
experts and be very

00:05:08.870 --> 00:05:13.050
skeptical of what they have to
say for the following reasons.

00:05:13.050 --> 00:05:19.470
One, experts know that humans
suffer from behavioral bias.

00:05:19.470 --> 00:05:22.540
So at another point in my
life-- almost 10 years ago--

00:05:22.540 --> 00:05:25.920
I actually got to hang
out with the Iraqi Army,

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:28.860
and we have two types of people.

00:05:28.860 --> 00:05:31.390
We have the rational
people-- which

00:05:31.390 --> 00:05:34.890
I happen to be part of this club
this time, usually I'm not--

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:37.630
we have irrational people.

00:05:37.630 --> 00:05:39.540
What do rational people do?

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:41.980
Well, we wear our Kevlars.

00:05:41.980 --> 00:05:42.940
Why?

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:47.230
Because if this hut back here
gets smashed with a mortar

00:05:47.230 --> 00:05:51.070
and a piece of cement goes
blazing toward your head,

00:05:51.070 --> 00:05:52.830
you want to have
something protecting you.

00:05:52.830 --> 00:05:54.740
So you wear Kevlar.

00:05:54.740 --> 00:05:57.740
We also bring extra ammunition.

00:05:57.740 --> 00:05:58.990
Why does that make sense?

00:05:58.990 --> 00:06:02.270
Well if you get shot at, it'd
be nice to shoot back, right?

00:06:02.270 --> 00:06:04.380
So we've got to bring
extra ammunition.

00:06:04.380 --> 00:06:07.600
We also need to bring a
source of water-- which

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:10.340
I don't know if you can see
on these two rational folks

00:06:10.340 --> 00:06:15.410
here-- because in 125 degree
weather, if you're not drinking

00:06:15.410 --> 00:06:17.980
and hydrating you're
going to probably die

00:06:17.980 --> 00:06:21.000
of heatstroke before you
die of an IED or something.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.640
So rational people
in this environment

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:25.910
do this sort of stuff.

00:06:25.910 --> 00:06:30.300
Then we've got
exhibit B. No Kevlar

00:06:30.300 --> 00:06:34.320
because wearing a Kevlar--
it's heavy, it's hot,

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:35.720
why would I want to wear that?

00:06:35.720 --> 00:06:37.110
I'm going to hold it.

00:06:37.110 --> 00:06:38.610
Ammunition?

00:06:38.610 --> 00:06:40.400
We don't need ammunition.

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:43.680
It's heavy, it's hot, I
don't want to carry it.

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:45.670
Leave that back at the barracks.

00:06:45.670 --> 00:06:48.650
And of course, don't
bring a source of water

00:06:48.650 --> 00:06:51.910
because in Arab culture
over there-- especially

00:06:51.910 --> 00:06:55.160
within the military ranks-- it's
kind of weak to drink water.

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:56.940
So we're not going
to do that, right?

00:06:56.940 --> 00:06:57.730
What's the point?

00:06:57.730 --> 00:07:01.590
The point is when we're
in distressed, emotional

00:07:01.590 --> 00:07:06.070
situations, we sometimes
do irrational things.

00:07:06.070 --> 00:07:08.950
And that's not to say
that in a financial market

00:07:08.950 --> 00:07:12.110
it's like being in a combat
zone, but in many respects

00:07:12.110 --> 00:07:12.860
it is.

00:07:12.860 --> 00:07:16.190
Because it's emotionally
charged, people on CNBC

00:07:16.190 --> 00:07:18.320
are saying the world's
going to blow up,

00:07:18.320 --> 00:07:22.320
and this is going to
inspire bad decision-making.

00:07:22.320 --> 00:07:26.050
So remember this, we're
influenced by bias.

00:07:26.050 --> 00:07:31.520
Even smart people that work
at Google suffer from bias.

00:07:31.520 --> 00:07:33.560
The other thing we've
got to recognize

00:07:33.560 --> 00:07:40.490
is that humans love stories
at the expense of evidence.

00:07:40.490 --> 00:07:43.180
So we've got the
fancy-schmancy hedge fund

00:07:43.180 --> 00:07:47.704
manager who's got his yacht and
his house in Martha's Vineyard.

00:07:47.704 --> 00:07:49.120
He's like hey, all
you've gotta do

00:07:49.120 --> 00:07:51.390
is do what I do and
you can have this, too.

00:07:51.390 --> 00:07:55.510
It's a great story-- good enough
for him, good enough for me.

00:07:55.510 --> 00:07:59.580
Even though the evidence
says time and time again

00:07:59.580 --> 00:08:02.670
when we buy expensive,
overpriced products,

00:08:02.670 --> 00:08:05.600
we allow the hedge
fund manager to afford

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:08.520
the yacht and the Martha's
Vineyard location.

00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:12.050
But we don't get afforded
that location because we're

00:08:12.050 --> 00:08:14.100
paying him all the fees.

00:08:14.100 --> 00:08:16.240
It's a great story.

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:20.110
People have studied the
human belief in stories

00:08:20.110 --> 00:08:24.180
at the expense of
evidence in great detail.

00:08:24.180 --> 00:08:27.120
BF Skinner almost
60, 70 years ago

00:08:27.120 --> 00:08:32.150
said why do human beings
believe in crazy stories

00:08:32.150 --> 00:08:34.580
even though there's so
much evidence to suggest

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:36.730
that their beliefs are insane?

00:08:36.730 --> 00:08:38.280
Why do they have
these superstitions?

00:08:38.280 --> 00:08:40.770
So they look at the pigeon,
because the pigeon's

00:08:40.770 --> 00:08:43.840
about as basic an animal
as you can get, right?

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:46.530
So what they do with these
pigeons, they say OK pigeons,

00:08:46.530 --> 00:08:48.400
we're going to make you hungry.

00:08:48.400 --> 00:08:50.580
And then we're going
to put you in a cage,

00:08:50.580 --> 00:08:54.275
and every five seconds a piece
a bird seed's going to pop out.

00:08:54.275 --> 00:08:55.720
And what do pigeons do?

00:08:55.720 --> 00:08:59.110
Pigeons are random, so they'll
bee-bop around their cage.

00:08:59.110 --> 00:09:03.662
And one will kick left, a piece
of bird seed will pop out.

00:09:03.662 --> 00:09:07.010
All right, nice,
eat my bird seed.

00:09:07.010 --> 00:09:08.810
Be-bopping around,
just by randomness

00:09:08.810 --> 00:09:11.070
they may kick again to the left.

00:09:11.070 --> 00:09:13.080
Bird seed popped out.

00:09:13.080 --> 00:09:17.770
Pigeons start thinking
if I kick to the left,

00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:19.420
bird seed comes out, right?

00:09:19.420 --> 00:09:21.790
And they start
developing this story,

00:09:21.790 --> 00:09:23.860
and they get this superstition.

00:09:23.860 --> 00:09:27.030
And then the researchers say
OK, now that we've established

00:09:27.030 --> 00:09:29.750
this story and this
superstition-- which is just

00:09:29.750 --> 00:09:33.770
based on noise-- can
we untrain this pigeon

00:09:33.770 --> 00:09:36.560
to stop believing that if
we give it enough evidence?

00:09:36.560 --> 00:09:39.130
So start tweaking it
around where it actually,

00:09:39.130 --> 00:09:42.060
systematically when it kicks
left, it doesn't get food.

00:09:42.060 --> 00:09:45.550
And what they find is
that once an animal--

00:09:45.550 --> 00:09:48.610
even a pigeon, and this
applies to humans--

00:09:48.610 --> 00:09:52.290
gets stuck in a story, trying
to give them a lot of evidence

00:09:52.290 --> 00:09:54.040
to convince them they're
wrong is actually

00:09:54.040 --> 00:09:58.690
incredibly difficult.
Because stories sell.

00:09:58.690 --> 00:10:00.480
Why is this important?

00:10:00.480 --> 00:10:04.400
Well, consumer
beware-- experts are

00:10:04.400 --> 00:10:08.830
very well-trained at
exploiting your bias

00:10:08.830 --> 00:10:12.560
and very well-trained at
telling you great stories.

00:10:12.560 --> 00:10:14.700
And the irony here is
that, in many respects,

00:10:14.700 --> 00:10:16.980
I should be
considered an expert.

00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:19.240
I don't know why, but
I was on the cover

00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:21.970
of Barron's last week,
I got a PhD in finance,

00:10:21.970 --> 00:10:25.450
I've written four books,
I'm doing all this research.

00:10:25.450 --> 00:10:29.400
So I'm the expert telling you
to not listen to the expert.

00:10:29.400 --> 00:10:31.790
Which is actually the best
advice you could possibly

00:10:31.790 --> 00:10:34.190
get from this discussion here.

00:10:34.190 --> 00:10:37.050
So everything I say, make
sure it goes in one ear

00:10:37.050 --> 00:10:39.580
and out the other, right?

00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:43.490
So with that disclaimer up
front, let's analyze how

00:10:43.490 --> 00:10:47.440
can we potentially add
evidence-based solutions

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:53.690
that can improve this
so-called 60/40 porfolio?

00:10:53.690 --> 00:10:55.900
And there's a lot of
metrics we can look at

00:10:55.900 --> 00:10:57.720
to try to improve
this thing, but we're

00:10:57.720 --> 00:11:01.060
going to focus on two here just
because of time constraints.

00:11:01.060 --> 00:11:03.470
And one is asset allocation.

00:11:03.470 --> 00:11:06.890
So trying to determine
how much stocks do we own?

00:11:06.890 --> 00:11:10.550
How much bond, how much
commodity, how much whatever?

00:11:10.550 --> 00:11:12.840
And the other one
is stock selection.

00:11:12.840 --> 00:11:14.670
Do we just go buy
a Vanguard fund

00:11:14.670 --> 00:11:17.060
or do we try to
become Warren Buffett

00:11:17.060 --> 00:11:19.560
and pick value
stocks or whatever?

00:11:19.560 --> 00:11:21.950
So we're going to walk through
both of these in detail

00:11:21.950 --> 00:11:25.720
and discuss how and why we
may want to add complexity,

00:11:25.720 --> 00:11:28.070
or maybe we don't want
to add complexity.

00:11:28.070 --> 00:11:30.700
So first, asset allocation.

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:32.780
So before I tell you
what's going on here,

00:11:32.780 --> 00:11:35.150
this paper is a 2009
paper in the "Review

00:11:35.150 --> 00:11:36.310
of Financial Studies."

00:11:36.310 --> 00:11:38.742
Which if you don't read
geeky finance research,

00:11:38.742 --> 00:11:40.200
you probably don't
know what it is.

00:11:40.200 --> 00:11:43.160
But it's a top
tier, A publication

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:47.260
that all the finance
professors have to be aware of.

00:11:47.260 --> 00:11:51.360
And what this paper shows--
or what these authors attempt

00:11:51.360 --> 00:11:53.670
to do-- is they
say listen, people

00:11:53.670 --> 00:11:57.760
who've won Nobel Prizes for
these ideas of mean variance

00:11:57.760 --> 00:12:00.640
analysis and modern
portfolio theory-- which

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:02.660
are rampant throughout society.

00:12:02.660 --> 00:12:04.690
I teach it in all of
my classes, everyone

00:12:04.690 --> 00:12:07.500
has to teach modern
portfolio theory.

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:09.570
But they asked a
simple question,

00:12:09.570 --> 00:12:14.540
does this crap actually
work in a practical sense?

00:12:14.540 --> 00:12:16.860
And they say, you know
what we're going to do?

00:12:16.860 --> 00:12:21.170
We're going to look at the 1
over N rule-- equal weighting

00:12:21.170 --> 00:12:21.850
of portfolios.

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:24.820
So if we have 10 assets-- i.e.

00:12:24.820 --> 00:12:29.730
N equals 10-- let's just
put 10% in each asset

00:12:29.730 --> 00:12:32.619
and use that as our
asset allocation scheme.

00:12:32.619 --> 00:12:34.410
And we're going to
compare that against all

00:12:34.410 --> 00:12:37.660
the whiz-bang fancy models
that have been published

00:12:37.660 --> 00:12:40.640
in academic research,
with tons of math

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:44.270
and nice closed-form solutions,
all these good things.

00:12:44.270 --> 00:12:46.590
And I'm just showing you
an example right here,

00:12:46.590 --> 00:12:48.590
and I'll just read
what the authors say.

00:12:48.590 --> 00:12:53.320
Of the 14 models we evaluate,
none is consistently

00:12:53.320 --> 00:12:56.840
better than 1 over N rule.

00:12:56.840 --> 00:12:58.210
That is remarkable.

00:12:58.210 --> 00:13:01.810
All that brain
damage and power that

00:13:01.810 --> 00:13:06.280
went into solving this stuff
that wins Nobel Prizes gets

00:13:06.280 --> 00:13:12.910
published, but has absolutely
limited practical benefit.

00:13:12.910 --> 00:13:14.270
That's remarkable.

00:13:14.270 --> 00:13:17.914
They're basically saying
this stuff doesn't work.

00:13:17.914 --> 00:13:20.330
Here's some of the evidence,
just to give you one example.

00:13:20.330 --> 00:13:23.030
They do this across
multiple asset classes.

00:13:23.030 --> 00:13:24.670
It's an academic
journal, so they've

00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:27.570
got to do robustness tests
until they're blue in the face.

00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:29.600
But since you're
on the x-axis here,

00:13:29.600 --> 00:13:31.455
you have the Sharpe
ratio-- which

00:13:31.455 --> 00:13:32.830
if you're not
familiar with that,

00:13:32.830 --> 00:13:36.710
it's just a risk-adjusted
benefit, higher is better--

00:13:36.710 --> 00:13:41.130
and they compare fancy
models against 1 over N

00:13:41.130 --> 00:13:44.060
when they're looking to
allocate across S&amp;P sectors.

00:13:44.060 --> 00:13:48.700
So you have utilities,
financials, whatever, energy.

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:50.830
We could use a fancy
optimization model

00:13:50.830 --> 00:13:52.880
to try to pick and
choose the weights,

00:13:52.880 --> 00:13:55.830
or we could just do 1 over N.

00:13:55.830 --> 00:14:00.860
And remarkably 1 over N-- which
is insanely easy and robust--

00:14:00.860 --> 00:14:03.630
has the highest Sharpe ratio.

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:06.250
So not only does it
equal their perform,

00:14:06.250 --> 00:14:10.140
it's actually beats
most of these things.

00:14:10.140 --> 00:14:11.790
What's the bottom line?

00:14:11.790 --> 00:14:17.430
When it comes asset allocation,
complexity does not work.

00:14:17.430 --> 00:14:18.670
It's just the evidence.

00:14:18.670 --> 00:14:21.210
So if someone tries
to sell you something

00:14:21.210 --> 00:14:25.530
that sounds really cool,
it probably is really cool.

00:14:25.530 --> 00:14:28.260
Remember, the evidence
doesn't back or support

00:14:28.260 --> 00:14:29.955
that it probably
works out of sample.

00:14:32.470 --> 00:14:34.230
So what could be the
implication of that?

00:14:34.230 --> 00:14:37.334
And this is just an example,
and these are all frameworks.

00:14:37.334 --> 00:14:39.500
I'm not saying you should
do this or your shouldn't.

00:14:39.500 --> 00:14:43.370
But we have our
baseline 60/40 up here,

00:14:43.370 --> 00:14:47.000
and we know that doing
things that are crazy complex

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:48.710
don't really add much value.

00:14:48.710 --> 00:14:51.710
But maybe we can add
one degree of complexity

00:14:51.710 --> 00:14:55.290
to build a little bit
more robust portfolio.

00:14:55.290 --> 00:14:57.400
So one idea out
there is presented

00:14:57.400 --> 00:14:59.960
by Meb Faber and Eric
Richardson in a great book

00:14:59.960 --> 00:15:01.870
called "The Ivy Portfolio."

00:15:01.870 --> 00:15:04.140
I think Meb's actually
spoke here before.

00:15:04.140 --> 00:15:07.070
And what he shows is
something really compelling.

00:15:07.070 --> 00:15:12.060
You can capture 90% to 95%
of the returns of endowments

00:15:12.060 --> 00:15:15.300
and very sophisticated
people by simply

00:15:15.300 --> 00:15:18.380
allocating-- in an
equal weight fashion--

00:15:18.380 --> 00:15:20.960
to five asset classes.

00:15:20.960 --> 00:15:24.030
Domestic equity,
international equity,

00:15:24.030 --> 00:15:27.290
real estate,
commodities, and bonds--

00:15:27.290 --> 00:15:30.320
which you could buy some
ETFs for next-to-nothing

00:15:30.320 --> 00:15:34.750
and capture the world's
risk premiums simply.

00:15:34.750 --> 00:15:40.540
What I do here is just map
that concept into this 60/40,

00:15:40.540 --> 00:15:44.250
and tell you why this might
make a little bit more sense

00:15:44.250 --> 00:15:47.820
at the margin than
a generic 60/40.

00:15:47.820 --> 00:15:50.030
You still have
your 60 over here,

00:15:50.030 --> 00:15:52.830
divvy it up-- domestic,
international--

00:15:52.830 --> 00:15:54.720
why does that make rough sense?

00:15:54.720 --> 00:15:57.660
Well, that about approximates
the market capitalization

00:15:57.660 --> 00:16:01.000
of US securities and
international securities.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.430
So you're kind of passively
capturing those risks.

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:09.730
And instead of doing 40%
all in on a fixed income

00:16:09.730 --> 00:16:14.025
instrument, what happens
if we turn into Zimbabwe?

00:16:14.025 --> 00:16:15.400
I'm not saying
that would happen,

00:16:15.400 --> 00:16:19.580
but there's a risk that we could
have a hyperinflation element.

00:16:19.580 --> 00:16:23.360
Maybe for our diversifier
bucket here and that 40%,

00:16:23.360 --> 00:16:28.240
we just break it in half--
20% real, 20% fixed.

00:16:28.240 --> 00:16:32.480
So instead of 40% fixed
income, maybe some real estate,

00:16:32.480 --> 00:16:36.640
commodities, kind of capture
in real hyperinflation hedges,

00:16:36.640 --> 00:16:38.790
and then stick with
that fixed income.

00:16:38.790 --> 00:16:41.910
So a small tweak that
might make this portfolio's

00:16:41.910 --> 00:16:46.150
overall architecture a little
bit more robust than 60/40.

00:16:46.150 --> 00:16:48.760
Not to say that
60/40's bad, but this

00:16:48.760 --> 00:16:54.270
may be one tweak you could use
to enhance it if you chose to.

00:16:54.270 --> 00:16:55.620
So real simple.

00:16:55.620 --> 00:16:57.110
I'm not even showing
results here,

00:16:57.110 --> 00:16:58.930
but this is also effective.

00:16:58.930 --> 00:17:01.100
All these things are
actually effective even

00:17:01.100 --> 00:17:02.689
though they're insanely easy.

00:17:02.689 --> 00:17:04.730
And they're also really
effective because they're

00:17:04.730 --> 00:17:07.280
really cheap, too.

00:17:07.280 --> 00:17:10.690
OK, that's asset allocation.

00:17:10.690 --> 00:17:12.450
Next is stock selection.

00:17:12.450 --> 00:17:16.369
And there's huge debates about
this, because the evidence is

00:17:16.369 --> 00:17:19.869
very clear that
over time-- if you

00:17:19.869 --> 00:17:22.180
look at the sample
of mutual funds,

00:17:22.180 --> 00:17:27.190
they bascially deliver the
S&amp;P minus a bunch of fees.

00:17:27.190 --> 00:17:28.890
That's not a good
idea, so that's

00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:31.310
why Jack Bogle says
well, let's just

00:17:31.310 --> 00:17:33.370
buy the Vanguard
fund for five BPs

00:17:33.370 --> 00:17:35.150
and you're going
to be better off.

00:17:35.150 --> 00:17:36.970
Why in the heck
would anyone want

00:17:36.970 --> 00:17:40.570
to try to be Warren Buffett?

00:17:40.570 --> 00:17:42.170
And that's a really
good question

00:17:42.170 --> 00:17:45.370
because as you'll find
out here, it's really hard

00:17:45.370 --> 00:17:46.710
to be Warren Buffett.

00:17:46.710 --> 00:17:50.100
And we also know that
for every active winner,

00:17:50.100 --> 00:17:52.720
there's got to be
an active loser.

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:54.520
So when you get
down to active game,

00:17:54.520 --> 00:17:56.367
it's not like there's
just free money,

00:17:56.367 --> 00:17:58.950
just because you're smarter than
everyone you're going to win.

00:17:58.950 --> 00:18:00.990
You're always
systematically having

00:18:00.990 --> 00:18:03.020
to take from someone else.

00:18:03.020 --> 00:18:05.330
Because in the end, it
basically is a zero sum game,

00:18:05.330 --> 00:18:06.538
for all intents and purposes.

00:18:09.200 --> 00:18:13.770
I happen to be a believer
in active stock selection,

00:18:13.770 --> 00:18:16.820
and I'll tell you
my story of why.

00:18:16.820 --> 00:18:20.250
So I used to hang
out with this guy.

00:18:20.250 --> 00:18:21.370
His name is Eugene Fama.

00:18:21.370 --> 00:18:23.650
He's now a famous Nobel
Prize winner, right?

00:18:23.650 --> 00:18:26.870
I'm doing my dissertation at
the you University of Chicago.

00:18:26.870 --> 00:18:28.790
I came back from
the Marines and I

00:18:28.790 --> 00:18:31.340
was feeling happy about myself.

00:18:31.340 --> 00:18:33.220
I was like, what
could I do that would

00:18:33.220 --> 00:18:37.260
be so ridiculous at
the school that it just

00:18:37.260 --> 00:18:38.370
would be interesting.

00:18:38.370 --> 00:18:42.300
I'm going to try to show Eugene
Fama, the guy who basically won

00:18:42.300 --> 00:18:45.130
the Nobel Prize for the
Effecient Market Hypothesis,

00:18:45.130 --> 00:18:48.120
that this value
investing stuff works.

00:18:48.120 --> 00:18:50.890
Because I've been reading
Warren Buffett, reading Ben

00:18:50.890 --> 00:18:54.300
Graham my whole life-- I
think this is compelling.

00:18:54.300 --> 00:18:56.170
I'm going to figure
out how to study

00:18:56.170 --> 00:18:58.750
this in a nice, robust way.

00:18:58.750 --> 00:19:01.250
So I go read 4000
reports submitted

00:19:01.250 --> 00:19:04.810
through this organization called
valueinvestorsclub.com, which

00:19:04.810 --> 00:19:07.050
is started by a guy named
Joel Greenblatt-- he was

00:19:07.050 --> 00:19:10.430
a famous hedge fund manager,
famous value investor--

00:19:10.430 --> 00:19:12.920
and I tabulate all
these results up.

00:19:12.920 --> 00:19:16.330
And I have right in my one
chapter of my dissertation,

00:19:16.330 --> 00:19:20.250
value investors have
stock picking skills.

00:19:20.250 --> 00:19:22.340
Send it to our friend
here who's probably

00:19:22.340 --> 00:19:24.960
the hardest working
man in finance.

00:19:24.960 --> 00:19:28.510
And of course, he immediately
responds in email,

00:19:28.510 --> 00:19:32.170
your conclusion has to be false.

00:19:32.170 --> 00:19:36.330
I'm like, oh crap, that just
wasted a year of my life.

00:19:36.330 --> 00:19:40.460
So I run down to Professor
Fama's office, I'm like,

00:19:40.460 --> 00:19:43.100
what do we mean it's false.

00:19:43.100 --> 00:19:46.390
Did I screw up in my
statistics or the study.

00:19:46.390 --> 00:19:48.370
He's like Wes, calm down.

00:19:48.370 --> 00:19:51.110
He's like, your
analysis is fine.

00:19:51.110 --> 00:19:54.880
But you can't say that value
investors have stock picking

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:55.830
skills.

00:19:55.830 --> 00:19:59.180
You have to say the
sample of value investors

00:19:59.180 --> 00:20:02.380
you analyzed have
stock picking skills.

00:20:02.380 --> 00:20:04.850
I was like, all right, so I
just got to change some words.

00:20:04.850 --> 00:20:07.030
He's like, yeah, words matter.

00:20:07.030 --> 00:20:09.170
I was like, roger that,
I'm out of this place.

00:20:09.170 --> 00:20:12.460
Sign the diploma, I'm
out of the pain train

00:20:12.460 --> 00:20:15.810
that you call the Chicago
Finance Ph.D. Program.

00:20:15.810 --> 00:20:17.510
And I walk out of
that place thinking,

00:20:17.510 --> 00:20:20.820
OK markets are not
perfectly efficient

00:20:20.820 --> 00:20:24.830
because there is evidence that
some people have this ability.

00:20:24.830 --> 00:20:28.230
And it seems to be compelling.

00:20:28.230 --> 00:20:29.570
More studies that have come out.

00:20:29.570 --> 00:20:33.080
So this is a study from Cliff
Asness and some of his friends.

00:20:33.080 --> 00:20:36.330
Very compelling paper published
in the Journal of Finance.

00:20:36.330 --> 00:20:40.590
Value and Momentum everywhere.

00:20:40.590 --> 00:20:42.850
And they highlight
that value, which

00:20:42.850 --> 00:20:48.510
is classified by just buying
cheap stuff everyone hates,

00:20:48.510 --> 00:20:50.860
and momentum, which
is buying securities

00:20:50.860 --> 00:20:55.300
that have strong relative
performance are everywhere.

00:20:55.300 --> 00:20:57.880
They're in every asset
class you could imagine.

00:20:57.880 --> 00:20:59.540
It's super compelling.

00:20:59.540 --> 00:21:01.830
And I've written books
dedicate each of this.

00:21:01.830 --> 00:21:04.620
So Quantitative Value is
a whole book dedicated

00:21:04.620 --> 00:21:07.135
to systematic value investing.

00:21:07.135 --> 00:21:10.680
We're interested in a manuscript
on another one on momentum.

00:21:10.680 --> 00:21:14.740
This stuff is baked in the cake.

00:21:14.740 --> 00:21:15.640
It has worked.

00:21:18.660 --> 00:21:21.000
So the natural question
is valuable momentum

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:22.300
are open secrets.

00:21:22.300 --> 00:21:25.220
They've been working
for over 100 years.

00:21:25.220 --> 00:21:28.074
Why isn't everyone doing this.

00:21:28.074 --> 00:21:29.490
And this gets to
the understanding

00:21:29.490 --> 00:21:32.820
of how and why active
investments actually

00:21:32.820 --> 00:21:35.039
work and are sustainable.

00:21:35.039 --> 00:21:36.580
And we have to have
a whole framework

00:21:36.580 --> 00:21:40.344
for this, called the sustainable
active investing framework.

00:21:40.344 --> 00:21:41.760
And the best way
to think about it

00:21:41.760 --> 00:21:43.590
it's like playing
at a poker game

00:21:43.590 --> 00:21:45.550
when you're in
the stock markets.

00:21:45.550 --> 00:21:48.756
We need to know at the
table who is the worst poker

00:21:48.756 --> 00:21:49.880
player at the table, right?

00:21:49.880 --> 00:21:53.350
Because we're going to need
to take from someone else

00:21:53.350 --> 00:21:56.020
because it's a zero sum game.

00:21:56.020 --> 00:21:57.700
But simultaneously,
you can't just

00:21:57.700 --> 00:22:01.130
know who the worst poker
player is at a poker table

00:22:01.130 --> 00:22:03.970
because if they're someone
way smarter than you,

00:22:03.970 --> 00:22:05.980
you're also the fish, right?

00:22:05.980 --> 00:22:10.520
So we need to know who are the
best poker players at the stock

00:22:10.520 --> 00:22:13.580
market investing table and
what are their capabilities

00:22:13.580 --> 00:22:15.260
and limitations.

00:22:15.260 --> 00:22:20.220
Only when we can identify
the bad poker player, which

00:22:20.220 --> 00:22:22.550
is usually represented
by investors that

00:22:22.550 --> 00:22:25.790
suffer from some sort of
systematic behavioral bias

00:22:25.790 --> 00:22:28.430
that actually can
influence stock prices,

00:22:28.430 --> 00:22:31.530
and simultaneously we
understand the capabilities

00:22:31.530 --> 00:22:34.140
and limitations of these
good poker players--

00:22:34.140 --> 00:22:37.590
either people with billions or
dollars or resources and access

00:22:37.590 --> 00:22:39.410
to all information in the world.

00:22:39.410 --> 00:22:44.170
Only then can we identify
a sustainable active

00:22:44.170 --> 00:22:46.070
opportunities.

00:22:46.070 --> 00:22:48.400
And the bottom
line is real active

00:22:48.400 --> 00:22:52.160
investing that works can't
be easy because it'll

00:22:52.160 --> 00:22:55.780
get arbitraged out immediately.

00:22:55.780 --> 00:22:59.890
Value investing is
a classic example

00:22:59.890 --> 00:23:03.110
of how we can take all
that mumbo jumbo theory

00:23:03.110 --> 00:23:05.110
and put a little meat
on the bones here.

00:23:05.110 --> 00:23:09.220
So what is value investing, what
is the so-called value anomaly,

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:10.770
just to give you a reference.

00:23:10.770 --> 00:23:14.050
So this is some results from a
paper we published a while ago.

00:23:14.050 --> 00:23:16.140
Essentially, value
investing and the value

00:23:16.140 --> 00:23:18.040
anomaly is this idea
that if you just

00:23:18.040 --> 00:23:22.900
buy cheap stocks, like this
sort, 1,000 securities on PE

00:23:22.900 --> 00:23:26.350
ratio, and you just
systematically every year buy

00:23:26.350 --> 00:23:29.750
the cheapest ones and you
create portfolios where you also

00:23:29.750 --> 00:23:32.870
buy the most expensive
ones, represented here

00:23:32.870 --> 00:23:36.710
by Glamor-- top
20% most expensive,

00:23:36.710 --> 00:23:41.560
top 20% cheapest-- over time
no matter how you figure out

00:23:41.560 --> 00:23:45.650
how we're going to measure
value, you get this spread.

00:23:45.650 --> 00:23:49.390
Of anywhere from 4%
to 7% in this sample.

00:23:49.390 --> 00:23:50.840
That's each year.

00:23:50.840 --> 00:23:53.750
If you compound 47%
for 40 years, that's

00:23:53.750 --> 00:23:56.150
the difference between being
Warren Buffett and being me,

00:23:56.150 --> 00:23:56.650
right?

00:23:56.650 --> 00:23:58.980
You're going to be
rich if you did this.

00:23:58.980 --> 00:24:01.100
So this is the anomaly.

00:24:01.100 --> 00:24:04.380
You just buy cheap stuff.

00:24:04.380 --> 00:24:06.690
So what is going on here.

00:24:06.690 --> 00:24:11.840
So back in the literature,
value investing and this anomaly

00:24:11.840 --> 00:24:13.610
can be explained by
one of two things.

00:24:13.610 --> 00:24:17.789
Extra risk or maybe
it's mis-pricing.

00:24:17.789 --> 00:24:19.080
How are we going to study this.

00:24:19.080 --> 00:24:21.146
Well Lakonishok,
Shleifer, and Vishny,

00:24:21.146 --> 00:24:24.825
in a Journal of Finance
1994 paper, do exactly this.

00:24:24.825 --> 00:24:27.860
This was over 20 years ago.

00:24:27.860 --> 00:24:29.690
They say, how are we
going to determine

00:24:29.690 --> 00:24:34.240
whether this is because of
extra risk or due to mispricing.

00:24:34.240 --> 00:24:36.200
So what they did is
they sourced securities

00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:38.420
on book to market in this case.

00:24:38.420 --> 00:24:41.830
Expensive to cheap.

00:24:41.830 --> 00:24:47.040
On our y-axis here is the past
five years earnings growth

00:24:47.040 --> 00:24:47.940
rates.

00:24:47.940 --> 00:24:52.860
And you notice is a monotonic
relationship between price

00:24:52.860 --> 00:24:56.070
and past fundamentals.

00:24:56.070 --> 00:24:58.710
What is the implied
market expectation

00:24:58.710 --> 00:25:00.270
embedded in these prices.

00:25:00.270 --> 00:25:04.620
Well, these securities
are expensive because it

00:25:04.620 --> 00:25:07.540
is necessarily implied
that that will continue.

00:25:07.540 --> 00:25:10.050
Why else would you pay a lot
of money for a stock, right?

00:25:10.050 --> 00:25:12.260
Why would you want
to buy Facebook

00:25:12.260 --> 00:25:15.750
at whatever PE it is right
now, unless you thought

00:25:15.750 --> 00:25:18.250
Facebook was going
to continue to have

00:25:18.250 --> 00:25:19.770
this amazing growth, right?

00:25:19.770 --> 00:25:22.440
So it's extrapolated
out into the future.

00:25:22.440 --> 00:25:24.210
That's why these are expensive.

00:25:24.210 --> 00:25:28.310
Similarly, down here in the
trash can, amongst the cheapest

00:25:28.310 --> 00:25:30.420
securities that no
one really likes,

00:25:30.420 --> 00:25:33.310
these are the dead
dinosaur companies

00:25:33.310 --> 00:25:37.510
or whatever it might be,
they're dead and dinosaured out

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:41.940
and cheap because they've
done poorly recently.

00:25:41.940 --> 00:25:44.020
And the implied
market expectation

00:25:44.020 --> 00:25:46.890
is they're probably going to
do poorly in the future, right?

00:25:46.890 --> 00:25:48.309
That's why they're cheap.

00:25:48.309 --> 00:25:50.850
If everyone thought they were
going to do well in the future,

00:25:50.850 --> 00:25:52.800
they would be over here.

00:25:52.800 --> 00:25:54.220
They're not.

00:25:54.220 --> 00:25:57.150
So we know the expectation
that's baked in the cake.

00:25:57.150 --> 00:26:00.040
This is going to continue.

00:26:00.040 --> 00:26:01.290
And this is going to continue.

00:26:01.290 --> 00:26:06.940
Well what actually happens in
the future-- systematic, meaner

00:26:06.940 --> 00:26:10.070
version in results.

00:26:10.070 --> 00:26:13.760
The gross stocks never
achieve, on average,

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:16.390
what the market thought
they were going to achieve.

00:26:16.390 --> 00:26:18.040
What was baked in the cake.

00:26:18.040 --> 00:26:23.050
Similarly, cheap trash stocks
were expected to basically

00:26:23.050 --> 00:26:27.410
all go bankrupt and on average
they never go all bankrupt,

00:26:27.410 --> 00:26:29.380
the world gets a
little bit better,

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:31.020
and there's [INAUDIBLE] version.

00:26:31.020 --> 00:26:34.340
So why does value work.

00:26:34.340 --> 00:26:38.440
And why does growth
or expensive not work.

00:26:38.440 --> 00:26:42.210
Because the price
valuation is essentially

00:26:42.210 --> 00:26:46.130
proxying for a bad
market expectation.

00:26:46.130 --> 00:26:48.970
So when you own
the cheap stocks,

00:26:48.970 --> 00:26:51.900
and it turns out it's
not as bad as thought,

00:26:51.900 --> 00:26:55.160
