00:43:48.910 --> 00:43:51.840
So the next question is
how can you simultaneously

00:43:51.840 --> 00:44:00.850
have value, which is essentially
an overreaction to-- we spend

00:44:00.850 --> 00:44:02.500
like a whole book
explaining this

00:44:02.500 --> 00:44:07.490
so I'll try to do this as simple
as possible here give me a sec.

00:44:07.490 --> 00:44:09.560
All right, so value
essentially seems

00:44:09.560 --> 00:44:13.540
to be driven by an
overreaction to crappy news

00:44:13.540 --> 00:44:14.540
in the short run, right?

00:44:14.540 --> 00:44:17.300
That systematically
mean reverse.

00:44:17.300 --> 00:44:19.740
And in theory we
make money on this

00:44:19.740 --> 00:44:23.200
because of mispricing because
that cheapness is essentially

00:44:23.200 --> 00:44:26.310
a proxy for market-wide
expectation errors.

00:44:26.310 --> 00:44:29.270
That we can use to use
that proxy as a signal

00:44:29.270 --> 00:44:32.210
to front run future market
expectations, right?

00:44:32.210 --> 00:44:34.080
Where people are
like, oh wow, you

00:44:34.080 --> 00:44:36.200
know IBM is not going bankrupt.

00:44:36.200 --> 00:44:37.990
It's obviously not
going to become Google

00:44:37.990 --> 00:44:40.960
but it's not as bad as
expected and you make money

00:44:40.960 --> 00:44:43.090
on the expectations
change, right?

00:44:43.090 --> 00:44:47.332
Momentum it turns out
it's a lot more complex.

00:44:47.332 --> 00:44:49.040
I think in the psychology
people are even

00:44:49.040 --> 00:44:52.970
a researcher are trying to
figure out the vast proportion

00:44:52.970 --> 00:44:55.485
of the empirical evidence.

00:44:55.485 --> 00:44:57.590
And I literally just
got done doing this

00:44:57.590 --> 00:44:59.230
because I just
wrote a book on it,

00:44:59.230 --> 00:45:01.950
is actually a
momentum, ironically,

00:45:01.950 --> 00:45:03.840
is actually the opposite.

00:45:03.840 --> 00:45:07.230
It's an under-reaction
to good news.

00:45:07.230 --> 00:45:09.960
So this price signal comes out.

00:45:09.960 --> 00:45:11.570
And you see this
price signal keep

00:45:11.570 --> 00:45:14.570
doing really well relative to
other securities out there.

00:45:14.570 --> 00:45:18.320
And prices tell you a lot about
information in the future.

00:45:18.320 --> 00:45:20.620
It's saying hey, this
thing is really good

00:45:20.620 --> 00:45:22.130
and it keeps going up.

00:45:22.130 --> 00:45:26.180
But for some reason, it
should be worth here,

00:45:26.180 --> 00:45:27.420
and the thing is moving up.

00:45:27.420 --> 00:45:30.390
But it doesn't immediately
go to fundamental value.

00:45:30.390 --> 00:45:33.130
There's like this
systematic under-reaction

00:45:33.130 --> 00:45:34.960
to this good news
that's coming out.

00:45:34.960 --> 00:45:37.610
And you can map that back
to like unexpected earnings

00:45:37.610 --> 00:45:38.850
releases and everything.

00:45:38.850 --> 00:45:42.170
So they're actually
kind of the same idea.

00:45:42.170 --> 00:45:45.740
One is just an overreaction
to crappy news.

00:45:45.740 --> 00:45:49.380
The other one is essentially an
under-reaction to positive news

00:45:49.380 --> 00:45:52.260
that's associated
with prices only.

00:45:52.260 --> 00:45:54.460
The value anomaly
right here, remember

00:45:54.460 --> 00:45:58.430
this is a price relative
to a fundamental.

00:45:58.430 --> 00:46:00.370
So that's why this is growth.

00:46:00.370 --> 00:46:01.580
And this is value.

00:46:01.580 --> 00:46:05.300
Momentum has nothing to
do with fundamentals.

00:46:05.300 --> 00:46:06.572
Only price.

00:46:06.572 --> 00:46:09.280
And if you actually look at
the overlaps of portfolios

00:46:09.280 --> 00:46:13.320
between growth securities
and high momentum

00:46:13.320 --> 00:46:17.100
securities-- the name-
they're actually really low.

00:46:17.100 --> 00:46:19.120
And you also see it in the data.

00:46:19.120 --> 00:46:24.570
Growth portfolios under-perform
the market by a wide margin.

00:46:24.570 --> 00:46:28.250
Momentum portfolios
kicks the markets butt.

00:46:28.250 --> 00:46:30.800
It's volatile as
heck, and it's crazy,

00:46:30.800 --> 00:46:33.820
but that growth in
momentum, even though they

00:46:33.820 --> 00:46:37.010
sound the same-- and most
people even in industry

00:46:37.010 --> 00:46:38.510
don't understand
this difference--

00:46:38.510 --> 00:46:40.280
they're totally different.

00:46:40.280 --> 00:46:43.080
Growth is about price
to the fundamental,

00:46:43.080 --> 00:46:45.790
which is a quotient.

00:46:45.790 --> 00:46:49.160
Momentum is all
about price only.

00:46:49.160 --> 00:46:54.571
And you can sometimes have
value stocks be momentum stocks,

00:46:54.571 --> 00:46:55.070
right?

00:46:55.070 --> 00:46:58.440
Similarly, you can have
expensive stocks be high

00:46:58.440 --> 00:46:59.800
momentum stocks.

00:46:59.800 --> 00:47:05.690
But momentum and value are kind
of different ideas out there.

00:47:05.690 --> 00:47:08.052
But it's very nuanced.

00:47:08.052 --> 00:47:12.290
And unless you geek out
and do source journal

00:47:12.290 --> 00:47:15.870
literature-- a lot of people are
like momentum is just growth.

00:47:15.870 --> 00:47:17.380
That's not true.

00:47:17.380 --> 00:47:19.520
Especially when you define
momentum as actually

00:47:19.520 --> 00:47:21.930
it's defined in
the literature that

00:47:21.930 --> 00:47:26.310
captures the actual anomaly
that everyone's talking about.

00:47:26.310 --> 00:47:29.265
I don't know if that
answers your question, but--

00:47:29.265 --> 00:47:30.640
AUDIENCE: I mean
it's like you're

00:47:30.640 --> 00:47:33.910
using price too, its PE--

00:47:33.910 --> 00:47:35.100
WESLEY GRAY: For this, yes.

00:47:35.100 --> 00:47:36.080
Yeah, exactly.

00:47:36.080 --> 00:47:38.670
AUDIENCE: It's
surprising that that

00:47:38.670 --> 00:47:42.510
correlates so well with the past
