AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] to
relate to growth, which

00:47:51.046 --> 00:47:53.002
is just based on price, right?

00:47:53.002 --> 00:47:54.460
WESLEY GRAY: Well,
priced earnings.

00:47:54.460 --> 00:47:55.260
Yeah.

00:47:55.260 --> 00:47:59.040
So this is a price
to fundamental ratio.

00:47:59.040 --> 00:48:01.760
And like I said, that's
one of the arguments

00:48:01.760 --> 00:48:03.570
of why this works.

00:48:03.570 --> 00:48:05.120
It's because price
to fundamentals

00:48:05.120 --> 00:48:08.660
basically proxy for an
expectation problem, right?

00:48:08.660 --> 00:48:11.480
On the growth side,
people think it's

00:48:11.480 --> 00:48:13.240
way better than
it ends up always

00:48:13.240 --> 00:48:15.900
being on average yet in value.

00:48:15.900 --> 00:48:18.209
But then again, momentum,
and this is a very new--

00:48:18.209 --> 00:48:20.000
and if I had a white
board I could actually

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:24.620
like write this up or little
better-- it's only about price.

00:48:24.620 --> 00:48:26.940
And there's a lot of
really interesting theories

00:48:26.940 --> 00:48:28.589
because one of the
things-- and this

00:48:28.589 --> 00:48:30.380
is something even I
don't fully understand,

00:48:30.380 --> 00:48:32.050
I don't think anyone
does, I'm just

00:48:32.050 --> 00:48:35.580
trying my best to finally
get it-- in general,

00:48:35.580 --> 00:48:38.120
values sink in
about fundamentals

00:48:38.120 --> 00:48:40.310
and prices move around
a fundamental, right?

00:48:40.310 --> 00:48:42.620
That's kind of at
the core theory

00:48:42.620 --> 00:48:44.810
of how this whole game works.

00:48:44.810 --> 00:48:46.300
But you know, George
Soros and some

00:48:46.300 --> 00:48:48.450
these guys they had this
idea of reflexivity.

00:48:48.450 --> 00:48:51.550
And I think you can see
it in Palo Alto, where

00:48:51.550 --> 00:48:57.640
prices might actually reverse
influence fundamentals, right?

00:48:57.640 --> 00:49:02.230
For example, LinkedIn, just a
while ago before they blew up,

00:49:02.230 --> 00:49:04.210
the price was way high.

00:49:04.210 --> 00:49:06.550
You could have your
options to your employees

00:49:06.550 --> 00:49:08.150
and that's fundamentally good.

00:49:08.150 --> 00:49:10.390
Price goes down
50%, let's just say

00:49:10.390 --> 00:49:12.160
that wasn't even
fundamental-related,

00:49:12.160 --> 00:49:13.870
how are you going
to attract talent.

00:49:13.870 --> 00:49:16.740
You know you've got all this bad
PR out there like, ah, LinkedIn

00:49:16.740 --> 00:49:17.640
is dying.

00:49:17.640 --> 00:49:20.530
And now just the
price movement itself,

00:49:20.530 --> 00:49:22.900
even if it was
non-fundamental-related

00:49:22.900 --> 00:49:26.080
can actually fundamentally
affect the firm, right?

00:49:26.080 --> 00:49:30.960
So there's one cause going from
fundamentals to price action.

00:49:30.960 --> 00:49:32.660
But I think more
and more-- and this

00:49:32.660 --> 00:49:36.250
is where it gets confusing-- you
can argue, I think justifiably,

00:49:36.250 --> 00:49:40.870
that prices themselves can
influence fundamentals, right?

00:49:40.870 --> 00:49:42.760
If you have a high
flying stock and you

00:49:42.760 --> 00:49:46.160
go sell stock equity
for way overvalued,

00:49:46.160 --> 00:49:49.465
you can fundamentally
create value for this firm.

00:49:52.050 --> 00:49:53.550
Because I used to
be like totally

00:49:53.550 --> 00:49:55.135
in the religion of
value investing.

00:49:55.135 --> 00:49:57.370
And it's has taken me
a while to come around

00:49:57.370 --> 00:49:58.780
to this whole momentum thing.

00:49:58.780 --> 00:50:02.800
But now I'm thinking, OK,
it's not just fundamentals

00:50:02.800 --> 00:50:04.820
and then prices move around you.

00:50:04.820 --> 00:50:08.570
Its prices can actually
influence the fundamentals.

00:50:08.570 --> 00:50:11.220
And if prices are moving up
and let's say fundamentally

00:50:11.220 --> 00:50:14.990
that's just the price signals
making the fundamentals change,

00:50:14.990 --> 00:50:17.830
this can be a proxy for
maybe non-linear benefits

00:50:17.830 --> 00:50:19.950
that the market doesn't
really appreciate yet.

00:50:19.950 --> 00:50:23.410
Because stocks moving up,
oh wow, our cost of capital

00:50:23.410 --> 00:50:25.037
is way lower than it used to be.

00:50:25.037 --> 00:50:26.620
Because everyone
just loves our stock,

00:50:26.620 --> 00:50:28.240
even if they overvalue it.

00:50:28.240 --> 00:50:29.990
That's great because
I can do acquisitions

00:50:29.990 --> 00:50:33.270
cheaper than the other guy
who has crappy price action.

00:50:33.270 --> 00:50:35.160
Because his cost of
capital is higher.

00:50:35.160 --> 00:50:38.120
So that momentum could
actually indirectly

00:50:38.120 --> 00:50:40.650
be affecting the fundamentals
but the market's not really

00:50:40.650 --> 00:50:42.170
appreciating that yet.

00:50:42.170 --> 00:50:45.360
And so I think momentum
is way more complex.

00:50:45.360 --> 00:50:47.510
That's why I think it
also works a lot better.

00:50:47.510 --> 00:50:49.300
It actually works way
better than value.

00:50:49.300 --> 00:50:51.460
Because it's totally
counter-intuitive.

00:50:51.460 --> 00:50:55.380
Who wants to be the bag holder
on a 52 week high stock, right?

00:50:55.380 --> 00:50:56.700
There's disposition effects.

00:50:56.700 --> 00:50:59.020
Most people, when
it's moving up,

00:50:59.020 --> 00:51:00.670
they want to book
the market, right?

00:51:00.670 --> 00:51:04.949
So you have supply shocks coming
on when things are moving up.

00:51:04.949 --> 00:51:06.740
Wheras when they're
moving down, everyone's

00:51:06.740 --> 00:51:07.800
like they want to hold it.

00:51:07.800 --> 00:51:10.008
They're like, oh, we don't
want to realize that loss.

00:51:10.008 --> 00:51:10.910
It's too painful.

00:51:10.910 --> 00:51:13.940
So there's a lot of weird
psychological things

00:51:13.940 --> 00:51:16.730
that they are involved
with momentum.

00:51:16.730 --> 00:51:19.250
And like I said, I don't
think anyone understands it

00:51:19.250 --> 00:51:22.170
as explicitly as value,
which is a little bit easier

00:51:22.170 --> 00:51:23.120
to understand.

00:51:23.120 --> 00:51:27.590
Momentum is somewhat
interesting.

00:51:27.590 --> 00:51:29.870
And it's certainly
one part behavioral

00:51:29.870 --> 00:51:32.330
driven, certainly
one part risk driven,

00:51:32.330 --> 00:51:34.840
because it's way more volatile.

00:51:34.840 --> 00:51:35.880
It's really interesting.

00:51:35.880 --> 00:51:37.599
And the value-momentum
combination

00:51:37.599 --> 00:51:39.140
is really interesting
because they're

00:51:39.140 --> 00:51:40.740
unrelated to each other.

00:51:40.740 --> 00:51:42.980
That's another
anomaly in itself.

00:51:42.980 --> 00:51:44.390
Value is kind of anomalous.

00:51:44.390 --> 00:51:45.909
Momentum is kind of anomalous.

00:51:45.909 --> 00:51:47.700
When you put them
together, because they're

00:51:47.700 --> 00:51:51.250
like yin and yang, you get all
