00:57:55.970 --> 00:57:58.010
and determine what's
cheap and expensive.

00:57:58.010 --> 00:58:00.750
But I mean momentum, do you
read technical indicators

00:58:00.750 --> 00:58:03.030
to get a sense of
what is that or are

00:58:03.030 --> 00:58:05.842
you looking at momentum against
the actual fundamentals?

00:58:05.842 --> 00:58:08.050
You said it's just based on
price, so I assume mostly

00:58:08.050 --> 00:58:08.550
[INAUDIBLE].

00:58:08.550 --> 00:58:11.330
WESLEY GRAY: Yeah, yeah, so
it's just pure price-based.

00:58:11.330 --> 00:58:14.690
So the classic academic
anomaly that's momentum

00:58:14.690 --> 00:58:16.880
is essential what you
do is, every month,

00:58:16.880 --> 00:58:19.480
say you have 1,000
securities, you just sort them

00:58:19.480 --> 00:58:22.930
on their past 12 month return--
just to keep this really easy.

00:58:22.930 --> 00:58:27.170
And it turns out that those
that are in the top say, 100,

00:58:27.170 --> 00:58:29.380
tend to outperform
the next month, right?

00:58:29.380 --> 00:58:33.050
And those in the bottom 100--
they were relatively weak

00:58:33.050 --> 00:58:35.450
and tend to continue to
under-perform, right?

00:58:35.450 --> 00:58:37.210
And you keep doing
this every month,

00:58:37.210 --> 00:58:39.180
you get this huge
momentum spread.

00:58:39.180 --> 00:58:43.890
Very simple, just 12 month look
back, sort, you get the spread.

00:58:43.890 --> 00:58:47.330
That's the most generic
version and that itself

00:58:47.330 --> 00:58:48.250
is really effective.

00:58:48.250 --> 00:58:50.070
But it's also painful as heck.

00:58:50.070 --> 00:58:52.330
Now I have a whole
book about this

00:58:52.330 --> 00:58:55.590
but, if you believe in
the behavioral theory,

00:58:55.590 --> 00:58:59.817
and you think it's an
under-reaction to fundamental

00:58:59.817 --> 00:59:01.400
news or fundamental
information that's

00:59:01.400 --> 00:59:03.110
going to impound those prices.

00:59:03.110 --> 00:59:04.490
And it's just empirical facts.

00:59:04.490 --> 00:59:06.770
You can Google it, it's
called Frog in the Pan.

00:59:06.770 --> 00:59:09.120
It's the name of the algorithm.

00:59:09.120 --> 00:59:13.490
The idea is that if the frog
is in the hot boiling water,

00:59:13.490 --> 00:59:16.270
they immediately know
and they jump out, right?

00:59:16.270 --> 00:59:19.910
You can also put a frog in
water and slowly heat it up

00:59:19.910 --> 00:59:21.889
and then they get killed
in the end, right?

00:59:21.889 --> 00:59:24.180
Because they have limited
attention to what's going on.

00:59:24.180 --> 00:59:25.200
They don't feel it.

00:59:25.200 --> 00:59:26.400
So same thing with momentum.

00:59:26.400 --> 00:59:29.380
If you tweak the algorithm where
instead of just generically

00:59:29.380 --> 00:59:31.890
buying all the best
relative performers,

00:59:31.890 --> 00:59:35.620
those top 100, what happens if
you have a biotech in there.

00:59:35.620 --> 00:59:38.910
It's up 100% because
yesterday it got FDA approval.

00:59:38.910 --> 00:59:40.740
That's like the
frog feels the heat.

00:59:40.740 --> 00:59:41.910
It jumps out.

00:59:41.910 --> 00:59:45.410
Everyone knows about, it's
on CNBC, it's all great.

00:59:45.410 --> 00:59:47.810
But what about these
momentum stocks.

00:59:47.810 --> 00:59:49.850
They're in the high
momentum bucket

00:59:49.850 --> 00:59:51.790
but they're just
slowly grinding there.

00:59:51.790 --> 00:59:54.050
It's like more of
a stable momentum.

00:59:54.050 --> 00:59:56.550
It's just like you see this
price movement, like 50

00:59:56.550 --> 00:59:58.850
BIPs over 200, 300 days.

00:59:58.850 --> 01:00:01.440
Versus like the ones
that just go up in a day.

01:00:01.440 --> 01:00:04.690
Well it turns out that
the momentum anomaly

01:00:04.690 --> 01:00:08.590
is almost exclusively driven
by those securities that

01:00:08.590 --> 01:00:11.850
are in that high momentum bucket
that had that slow grinding

01:00:11.850 --> 01:00:12.540
momentum.

01:00:12.540 --> 01:00:15.790
Because if you get like the
biotech that shoots up 100%,

01:00:15.790 --> 01:00:17.490
those are efficient
market price.

01:00:17.490 --> 01:00:19.930
They're just high risk,
high reward deals.

01:00:19.930 --> 01:00:21.900
And that goes back to
the behavioral bias.

01:00:21.900 --> 01:00:24.540
It's an under-reaction to news.

01:00:24.540 --> 01:00:28.760
Where when you see the FDA
approval, it goes up 100%--

01:00:28.760 --> 01:00:31.210
everyone sees it,
everyone reacts to it.

01:00:31.210 --> 01:00:33.990
Whereas this small grinding
kind of information

01:00:33.990 --> 01:00:36.440
that's being released
over time that's more

01:00:36.440 --> 01:00:38.230
likely to be under-reacted to.

01:00:38.230 --> 01:00:40.240
And that's exactly what
we've seen in the data.

01:00:40.240 --> 01:00:41.664
It's still painful.

01:00:41.664 --> 01:00:42.580
But that's all you do.

01:00:42.580 --> 01:00:44.700
You don't need to
make it that complex.

01:00:44.700 --> 01:00:47.320
And there's some seasonality
things and what have you,

01:00:47.320 --> 01:00:49.430
but you just e-mail me
when the book comes out,

01:00:49.430 --> 01:00:52.360
[INAUDIBLE] there's a
whole book dedicated to it.

01:00:52.360 --> 01:00:54.980
But the summary is a
slow moving momentum

01:00:54.980 --> 01:00:58.951
is better than wacky moment.

