01:05:27.210 --> 01:05:28.959
out there that are
capturing that momentum

01:05:28.959 --> 01:05:31.360
premium you were talking about?

01:05:31.360 --> 01:05:33.370
WESLEY GRAY: There are.

01:05:33.370 --> 01:05:38.220
I don't want to talk my book
here but here's the thing.

01:05:38.220 --> 01:05:41.230
Another thing to understand
about active management

01:05:41.230 --> 01:05:44.460
is there's the business
of active manager, right?

01:05:44.460 --> 01:05:47.240
And if I'm a large
institutional firm--

01:05:47.240 --> 01:05:50.630
and really I get paid
on just assets-- when

01:05:50.630 --> 01:05:54.380
I'm designing a product,
most products that work

01:05:54.380 --> 01:05:56.430
are going to have some
scalability issue.

01:05:56.430 --> 01:05:58.600
Momentum is a perfect
example where momentum,

01:05:58.600 --> 01:06:00.590
to get it to be
effective, it has

01:06:00.590 --> 01:06:02.850
to have relatively
high turnover, right?

01:06:02.850 --> 01:06:04.990
That's how that system works.

01:06:04.990 --> 01:06:07.140
But the problem with the
relatively high turnover

01:06:07.140 --> 01:06:09.480
is its relatively
high frictional costs.

01:06:09.480 --> 01:06:13.420
So if I try to jam a billion
dollars into this thing,

01:06:13.420 --> 01:06:16.200
I can design the
program one way.

01:06:16.200 --> 01:06:19.920
If I need to jam $20
billion in this program,

01:06:19.920 --> 01:06:23.090
I need to maybe need to
diversify and dilute this thing

01:06:23.090 --> 01:06:25.600
out so it can take on capacity.

01:06:25.600 --> 01:06:28.020
Which is now a
business decision,

01:06:28.020 --> 01:06:30.620
not necessarily
like an optimize,

01:06:30.620 --> 01:06:33.610
capture the premium
over time decision.

01:06:33.610 --> 01:06:36.282
And so just when
you buy products,

01:06:36.282 --> 01:06:38.240
think through the economics
of the manufacturer

01:06:38.240 --> 01:06:39.570
of that product.

01:06:39.570 --> 01:06:41.940
Are they building
this for performance.

01:06:41.940 --> 01:06:43.770
Or are they building
this for scalability

01:06:43.770 --> 01:06:47.040
and to try to jam as many
assets into it as possible.

01:06:47.040 --> 01:06:50.770
And because markets at the
margin are insanely efficient,

01:06:50.770 --> 01:06:52.780
the meaning is
like Buffett says,

01:06:52.780 --> 01:06:57.170
if you gave us $20, $30 billion,
you'd want to fire us, right?

01:06:57.170 --> 01:07:00.150
Because we can't do
active, weird things

01:07:00.150 --> 01:07:02.650
anymore because you've
got to jam too much money

01:07:02.650 --> 01:07:03.960
through the same door.

01:07:03.960 --> 01:07:07.890
And so yeah, that's the problem.

01:07:07.890 --> 01:07:09.700
When you're looking
at products, like

01:07:09.700 --> 01:07:14.504
understand the situation of that
manufacturer of this product.

01:07:14.504 --> 01:07:15.920
Are they trying
to build something

01:07:15.920 --> 01:07:18.230
that works in
expectation or are they

01:07:18.230 --> 01:07:20.530
trying to form a
portfolio where they just

01:07:20.530 --> 01:07:23.510
go and have a bunch of salesman
jam it down your throat,

01:07:23.510 --> 01:07:26.830
but it can take on like
$20 billion, right?

01:07:26.830 --> 01:07:30.070
And maybe you, as the buyer
of that product-- everything's

01:07:30.070 --> 01:07:32.930
called momentum,
everything's called value,

01:07:32.930 --> 01:07:36.070
but the construction of
these things matters a lot.

01:07:36.070 --> 01:07:37.770
Because the name
doesn't mean anything.

01:07:37.770 --> 01:07:41.860
It's really about what's the
engineering of the product.

01:07:41.860 --> 01:07:44.430
Yeah so there's definitely
momentum things out there

01:07:44.430 --> 01:07:45.130
and we do that.

01:07:45.130 --> 01:07:47.810
But I don't want to-- I mean
you we're all about education,

01:07:47.810 --> 01:07:50.640
go learn on your own
and we can talk offline.

01:07:50.640 --> 01:07:54.160
But there are some
people-- Alpha Architect--

01:07:54.160 --> 01:07:57.460
that is trying to build like,
generally intellectually

01:07:57.460 --> 01:08:00.180
honest products that
have limited scalability.

01:08:00.180 --> 01:08:04.110
And we're trying to do them like
the intellectually honest way.

01:08:04.110 --> 01:08:05.840
And we just tell
people like, this

01:08:05.840 --> 01:08:07.620
is going to suck sometimes.

01:08:07.620 --> 01:08:09.380
But if you have a
horizon duration,

01:08:09.380 --> 01:08:11.870
this is at least the honest
way to go about this.

01:08:11.870 --> 01:08:14.924
But unless you're wired to do
that, you shouldn't to do that.

01:08:14.924 --> 01:08:17.090
But not many people do it
because they'd rather just

01:08:17.090 --> 01:08:20.560
raise like 100 billion assets
and charge a lot of money

01:08:20.560 --> 01:08:21.549
for it.

01:08:21.549 --> 01:08:22.229
So.

01:08:22.229 --> 01:08:24.770
AUDIENCE: All right, so the next
question is related to that.

01:08:24.770 --> 01:08:27.149
Which is that some
strategies just suck.

01:08:27.149 --> 01:08:28.840
Other strategies
are good, but they

01:08:28.840 --> 01:08:30.069
are going to suck at times.

01:08:30.069 --> 01:08:31.110
How do you differentiate?

01:08:33.510 --> 01:08:36.153
WESLEY GRAY: Well let me
step back here, actually.

01:08:39.470 --> 01:08:42.550
There's two worlds
out there, right?

01:08:42.550 --> 01:08:45.649
There's the investment
horizon game, which

01:08:45.649 --> 01:08:47.310
is what I'm talking about here.

01:08:47.310 --> 01:08:49.970
There actually is
another game out there

01:08:49.970 --> 01:08:52.040
of the best poker player game.

01:08:52.040 --> 01:08:53.279
This is a real game.

01:08:53.279 --> 01:08:55.930
It's like proprietary
trading hedge funds

01:08:55.930 --> 01:09:00.960
where there are strategies you
can devise with a ton of work.

01:09:00.960 --> 01:09:03.130
Where you get some
competitive information edge

01:09:03.130 --> 01:09:05.260
where in the short
term, it's actually

01:09:05.260 --> 01:09:07.580
like a true edge, right?

01:09:07.580 --> 01:09:09.910
They always have
capacity constraints.

01:09:09.910 --> 01:09:11.930
And they may not
even be that painful.

01:09:11.930 --> 01:09:14.460
But the issue there is
that's the trading business.

01:09:14.460 --> 01:09:16.293
You're always having
to adapt because you're

01:09:16.293 --> 01:09:18.630
competing against all
the Google people, right?

01:09:18.630 --> 01:09:21.620
And all the physics PhDs--
where you find a system,

01:09:21.620 --> 01:09:24.119
it works for a while,
all of a sudden

01:09:24.119 --> 01:09:26.410
it's actually not even painful
because you can leverage

01:09:26.410 --> 01:09:27.700
out and make a lot of money.

01:09:27.700 --> 01:09:29.040
But it starts to decay.

01:09:29.040 --> 01:09:32.359
And you can always be on the R&amp;D
game of inventing the next best

01:09:32.359 --> 01:09:33.470
trading strategy.

01:09:33.470 --> 01:09:36.450
Those aren't sustainable
opportunities.

01:09:36.450 --> 01:09:38.760
They're not painful
and they work,

01:09:38.760 --> 01:09:40.010
but that's different business.

01:09:40.010 --> 01:09:42.220
That's the trading business.

01:09:42.220 --> 01:09:45.630
Back to here, basically
the way to look at it--

01:09:45.630 --> 01:09:51.050
the more pain and the more
delegated asset managers

01:09:51.050 --> 01:09:54.189
would not want to do
this, in expectation

01:09:54.189 --> 01:09:56.790
that's probably going to
work better at the margin.

01:09:56.790 --> 01:09:59.350
So whatever strategy
to do, if it's

01:09:59.350 --> 01:10:02.340
less full on a
relative tracking--

01:10:02.340 --> 01:10:04.840
like it attracts
index with less pain--

01:10:04.840 --> 01:10:07.660
it's going to generally
work less well.

01:10:07.660 --> 01:10:10.550
It's just a general rule
because of competition.

01:10:10.550 --> 01:10:13.240
If it's less painful and
there's less likelihood

01:10:13.240 --> 01:10:15.710
of getting fired,
it's probably not

01:10:15.710 --> 01:10:18.890
going to have as much kind
of career risk premium built

01:10:18.890 --> 01:10:19.660
into it.

01:10:19.660 --> 01:10:22.140
Where if it's more painful,
and it's more likely

01:10:22.140 --> 01:10:26.560
the delegated asset
manager gets fired,

01:10:26.560 --> 01:10:29.240
you're going to capture a
bigger career risk premium.

01:10:29.240 --> 01:10:31.400
And so it's not that
ones good or bad.

01:10:31.400 --> 01:10:35.280
It's really about pick
your poison essentially--

01:10:35.280 --> 01:10:37.970
is what I would say.

01:10:37.970 --> 01:10:40.960
So it just depends how much
bang you want for your book.

01:10:40.960 --> 01:10:44.380
And if you're better suited to
take careers pain than maybe

01:10:44.380 --> 01:10:46.140
other people are.

01:10:46.140 --> 01:10:48.900
And DIY people are very
well-suited to take career risk

01:10:48.900 --> 01:10:51.510
pain because you can't
fire yourself, right?

01:10:51.510 --> 01:10:55.710
So that's why disintermediation
is a beautiful thing.

01:10:55.710 --> 01:10:58.350
Because if you're Google
engineer and you sit here,

01:10:58.350 --> 01:11:01.815
like learn about all this stuff,
and you have the real horizon,

01:11:01.815 --> 01:11:03.190
and you understand
how and why it

01:11:03.190 --> 01:11:08.160
m you're in the perfect
position to take on career risk.

01:11:08.160 --> 01:11:10.100
Because it's not priced for you.

01:11:10.100 --> 01:11:14.170
It's priced for delegated asset
managers, not as an individual.

01:11:14.170 --> 01:11:15.490
You can just eat it.

01:11:15.490 --> 01:11:18.270
Because what are you going
to do, fire yourself?

01:11:18.270 --> 01:11:21.065
You can capture that
premium better than anyone

01:11:21.065 --> 01:11:22.690
but the problem is
you've got to invest

01:11:22.690 --> 01:11:24.430
a lot of time and
knowledge and education

01:11:24.430 --> 01:11:28.630
and figure out how it works, so.

01:11:28.630 --> 01:11:30.358
Sir?

01:11:30.358 --> 01:11:33.921
AUDIENCE: Regarding
individual investors,

01:11:33.921 --> 01:11:35.546
it seems like the
general strategy here

01:11:35.546 --> 01:11:37.416
is that because a lot
of people [INAUDIBLE].

