01:11:52.174 --> 01:11:53.882
seems like it'd be a
wide range of people

01:11:53.882 --> 01:11:56.010
losing money and making
money in that process.

01:11:56.010 --> 01:11:58.150
WESLEY GRAY: Yeah, there
is a huge wide range.

01:11:58.150 --> 01:12:01.530
But again, it goes
back to-- I believe

01:12:01.530 --> 01:12:04.190
there's supposed to be,
in theory, like risk

01:12:04.190 --> 01:12:06.880
premiums associated with
taking on risk, right?

01:12:06.880 --> 01:12:09.390
Equity risk premium, you don't
know what's going to happen.

01:12:09.390 --> 01:12:12.540
I think embedded in a lot
of strategies and algorithms

01:12:12.540 --> 01:12:14.190
is career risk premium.

01:12:14.190 --> 01:12:17.170
Because the people that manage
the billions and hundreds

01:12:17.170 --> 01:12:21.030
of billions of dollars, they
need to maintain that business.

01:12:21.030 --> 01:12:22.810
And they know that
if you deviate

01:12:22.810 --> 01:12:26.020
a small amount from an index,
you're not going to get fired.

01:12:26.020 --> 01:12:27.800
So you can earn a
little marginal spread

01:12:27.800 --> 01:12:29.270
over the Vanguard
guys because you

01:12:29.270 --> 01:12:32.100
can charge higher for
effectively what they're doing.

01:12:32.100 --> 01:12:34.230
And that's a great
business decision.

01:12:34.230 --> 01:12:36.280
Take minimal career
risk, make it

01:12:36.280 --> 01:12:38.800
a little bit different but
never too much different,

01:12:38.800 --> 01:12:41.470
because you can lose your AUN
and lose your whole business

01:12:41.470 --> 01:12:42.820
model.

01:12:42.820 --> 01:12:45.220
But as you get strategies
that get further and further

01:12:45.220 --> 01:12:48.890
away where they can go 10%
under the index, 10% over

01:12:48.890 --> 01:12:52.500
and go crazy, there's going
to be a premium there.

01:12:52.500 --> 01:12:54.790
Because the marginal
price setter

01:12:54.790 --> 01:12:57.680
is these institutions that
are the smart poker players.

01:12:57.680 --> 01:13:00.260
And they all know this
too they just won't do it

01:13:00.260 --> 01:13:01.850
because it's too risky.

01:13:01.850 --> 01:13:05.480
And their client base
is not hyper educated

01:13:05.480 --> 01:13:08.110
and they're not Warren Buffet's,
they're like mom and pops

01:13:08.110 --> 01:13:10.180
who look at their
statement are like,

01:13:10.180 --> 01:13:13.580
what, three years down, like
this guys out here and sell it.

01:13:13.580 --> 01:13:16.280
So there's a premium
I think that's priced

01:13:16.280 --> 01:13:20.040
in systems and strategies that
basically eat career risk.

01:13:20.040 --> 01:13:21.790
Because the marginal
price setters

01:13:21.790 --> 01:13:23.849
are the smart poker
players in the world.

01:13:23.849 --> 01:13:25.390
And they don't want
to eat that risk.

01:13:25.390 --> 01:13:28.031
Because that's painful and they
like to keep their business,

01:13:28.031 --> 01:13:28.530
right?

01:13:28.530 --> 01:13:31.570
And that's just I think
the equilibrium that

01:13:31.570 --> 01:13:32.487
actually has happened.

01:13:32.487 --> 01:13:34.653
AUDIENCE: Since there is a
model like, because we're

01:13:34.653 --> 01:13:37.061
an individual that won't
lose their job over this

01:13:37.061 --> 01:13:38.686
necessarily, you can
take greater risks

01:13:38.686 --> 01:13:40.480
than an institutional investor--

01:13:40.480 --> 01:13:43.460
WESLEY GRAY: You can
take greater career risk.

01:13:43.460 --> 01:13:47.540
Because remember, there's real
risk, which in theory, like

01:13:47.540 --> 01:13:50.740
in economics, is how like
the risk is correlated

01:13:50.740 --> 01:13:52.530
with like your
consumption over time

01:13:52.530 --> 01:13:55.700
or whatever wacky
macroeconomic model.

01:13:55.700 --> 01:13:57.950
But you're a position
to take the career

01:13:57.950 --> 01:14:00.100
risk, which is relative risk.

01:14:00.100 --> 01:14:02.540
So I always tell people,
imagine you're an alien.

01:14:02.540 --> 01:14:05.880
And you land on
the world in 1927.

01:14:05.880 --> 01:14:08.200
And the alien's like,
I got two options.

01:14:08.200 --> 01:14:11.020
I can buy this S&amp;P
thing that makes

01:14:11.020 --> 01:14:14.640
9% a year with an 80% drawdown
or whatever it is, right?

01:14:14.640 --> 01:14:18.120
You can buy this other thing
called value and it makes,

01:14:18.120 --> 01:14:21.570
let's say 12% a year
at 80% drawdowns.

01:14:21.570 --> 01:14:24.950
The alien, who doesn't care
about what S&amp;P because he's not

01:14:24.950 --> 01:14:27.380
benchmarking or whatever,
he's like, well yeah,

01:14:27.380 --> 01:14:29.250
do this other one, of course.

01:14:29.250 --> 01:14:33.220
But if the alien is now
a delegated agent working

01:14:33.220 --> 01:14:37.130
on behalf of others and he's
benchmarked against that S&amp;P

01:14:37.130 --> 01:14:40.340
products, and he has
now a business reason

01:14:40.340 --> 01:14:43.460
to like kind of not deviate
too much from that, in theory,

01:14:43.460 --> 01:14:45.960
he would be all in on
this value strategy.

01:14:45.960 --> 01:14:48.300
But because there's
this pricing,

01:14:48.300 --> 01:14:51.510
he's always benchmarked
against S&amp;P,

01:14:51.510 --> 01:14:53.810
